### Tracking Progress

After completing each task, update `tasks.md` in the change directory (`{{task.changePath}}`) to mark it as done:
- Change `- [ ]` to `- [x]` for completed tasks
- This keeps the checklist in sync with actual progress

### Development Process

**TDD requirement**: If the task introduces new code (functions, classes, modules), use the skill `test-driven-development`.

**Skip test-driven-development when**:
- Infrastructure/config tasks (CI, build, linting setup)
- The task IS writing tests or e2e tests 
  - Never use Mocks on E2E tests, the idea is to stress the real system with real APIs. Unless the user explicitly asked to use mocks.
- Writing frontend or UI/UX code. 
  - Here you should favor happy paths and basic unhappy flows using e2e/playwright tests
  - Apply TDD in E2E imagining you are the user
  - Use the `vercel-react-best-practices` skill when working with React.
  - Use the `webapp-testing` skill to run your tests
  - Use the `frontend-design` skill for design tasks.
- Pure refactoring with existing test coverage

4. Verify the chunk works before proceeding

### Red Flags — STOP Immediately

If you catch yourself thinking any of these, you are about to violate pacing:

- "Let me just finish this related section too"
- "These two sections are really one logical unit"
- "It would be cleaner to do both together"
- "I'm already in the zone, why stop?"
- "The next section is trivial, it'll take 2 minutes"

**All of these mean: Signal completion NOW. The next section is the next session.**

### Self-Check Before Signaling

Before signaling completion of a section, verify:

- [ ] Code compiles/type-checks without errors
- [ ] New functionality is wired up and callable
- [ ] If it's a UI/frontend task use the `webapp-testing` skill to verify it works
- [ ] No TODO comments left unaddressed
- [ ] Tests pass for the changed code
- [ ] Code follows project style guidelines

- [ ] Remove AI code slop
Check the current changes (staged, unstaged, or commit diffs, prompt the user if unclear), and remove all AI generated slop introduced in this branch.

This includes:

- Extra comments that a human wouldn't add or is inconsistent with the rest of the file
- Extra defensive checks or try/catch blocks that are abnormal for that area of the codebase (especially if called by trusted / validated codepaths)
- Casts to any to get around type issues
- Any other style that is inconsistent with the file
- also be mindful about deadcode, redeclared functions, DRY, YAGNI, and also for reinventing the wheel (recreating functionalities that already exist in the codebase, skipping existing utilities/packages patterns like not using the infra logger and using console.log)

